"103A":{"department":"EDUC","number":"103A","title":"Tutoring: Seeing a Child through Literacy (EDUC 203A)","description":"Experience tutoring grade school readers in a low income community near Stanford under supervision. Training in tutoring; the role of instruction in developing literacy; challenges facing low income students and those whose first language is not English. How to see school and print through the eyes of a child. Ravenswood Reads tutors encouraged to enroll. Service Learning Course (certified by Haas Center).","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":["DB-SocSci"],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"19:15:00","end":"21:05:00"}]}],[],[]]},
"103B":{"department":"EDUC","number":"103B","title":"Race, Ethnicity, and Linguistic Diversity in Classrooms: Sociocultural Theory and Practices (AFRICAAM 106, CSRE 103B, EDUC 337)","description":"Focus is on classrooms with students from diverse racial, ethnic and linguistic backgrounds. Studies, writing, and media representation of urban and diverse school settings; implications for transforming teaching and learning. Issues related to developing teachers with attitudes, dispositions, and skills necessary to teach diverse students.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":["WAY-ED"],"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"17:15:00","end":"20:05:00"}]}]]},
"104Q":{"department":"EDUC","number":"104Q","title":"\"Give Me the Child Until He is Seven...\" The Early Roots of Human Behavior","description":"A growing body of evidence suggests that the roots of behavior are to be found in early childhood. These early behaviors have a direct effect on the quality of a child's educational experience.  The educational experience, in turn, is a principal determinant of many adult outcomes that affect wellbeing.  This course will explore how early social forces, psychological influences, and biological systems combine to affect human behavior in early childhood, in the educational experience, and throughout the life course.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["Writing 2"],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"13:15:00","end":"14:30:00"}]}],[],[]]},
"109X":{"department":"EDUC","number":"109X","title":"Educational Issues in Contemporary China (EDUC 309X)","description":"Reforms such as the decentralization of school finance, emergence of private schools, expansion of higher education, and reframing of educational policy to focus on issues of quality. Have these reforms exacerbated educational inequality.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"14:15:00","end":"17:05:00"}]}]]},
"111":{"department":"EDUC","number":"111","title":"The Young Adult Novel: A Literature For and About Adolescents","description":"For undergraduates considering teaching or working with adolescents, and for those planning to apply to the coterminal program in the Stanford Teacher Education program (STEP). Students work together to define the genre of young adult novels. What they reveal about adolescence in America. How to read and teach young adult literature.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"15:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}]]},
