"114N":{"department":"EDUC","number":"114N","title":"Growing Up Bilingual (CHILATST 14N, CSRE 14N)","description":"This course is a Freshman Introductory Seminar that has as its purpose introducing students to the sociolinguistic study of bilingualism by focusing on bilingual communities in this country and on bilingual individuals who use two languages in their everyday lives. Much attention is given to the history, significance, and consequences of language contact in the United States. The course focuses on the experiences of long-term US minority populations as well as that of recent immigrants.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":["WAY-ED","WAY-SI"],"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,true,false],"start":"10:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}],[]]},
"117":{"department":"EDUC","number":"117","title":"Research and Policy on Postsecondary Access (EDUC 417)","description":"The transition from high school to college. K-16 course focusing on high school preparation, college choice, remediation, pathways to college, and first-year adjustment. The role of educational policy in postsecondary access. Service Learning Course (certified by Haas Center).","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"09:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}],[]]},
"120C":{"department":"EDUC","number":"120C","title":"Education and Society (EDUC 220C, SOC 130, SOC 230)","description":"The effects of schools and schooling on individuals, the stratification system, and society. Education as socializing individuals and as legitimizing social institutions. The social and individual factors affecting the expansion of schooling, individual educational attainment, and the organizational structure of schooling.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":["DB-SocSci"],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,true,false,true],"start":"11:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}],[],[]],"secondary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"13:15:00","end":"14:05:00"}]},{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"11:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}],[],[]]},
"126A":{"department":"EDUC","number":"126A","title":"Introduction to Public Service Leadership","description":"Offered through the Haas Center for Public Service.  A foundation and vision for a future of public service leadership. Students identify personal values and assess strengths as leaders. The ethics of public service and leadership theory.","min_units":1,"max_units":2,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"16:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}],[]]},
"126B":{"department":"EDUC","number":"126B","title":"Public Service Leadership Program Practicum","description":"This course is for students in the Public Service Leadership Program offered through the Haas Center for Public Service. Designed as a follow-up course to EDUC 126A: Introduction to Public Service Leadership, the PSLP Practicum provides an opportunity for PSLP students to reflect on their own leadership experiences and to learn from each other's leadership experiences while continuing to build a community of peer service leaders. The PSLP Practicum will meet every other week throughout the quarter.","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"16:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"16:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}]]},
"130":{"department":"EDUC","number":"130","title":"Introduction to Counseling (PSYCH 148)","description":"The goal of counseling is to help others to create more satisfying lives for themselves.  Clients learn to create and capitalize on unexpected events to open up new opportunities.  The success of counseling is judged, not by the words and actions of the counselor, but by the progress that the client makes in the real world after counseling itself is ended.  Students are encouraged to exert their full efforts within reasonable time limits to improve their competence.","min_units":3,"max_units":3,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"15:15:00","end":"17:05:00"}]}],[]]},
