"306D":{"department":"EDUC","number":"306D","title":"World, Societal, and Educational Change: Comparative Perspectives (EDUC 136, SOC 231)","description":"Theoretical perspectives and empirical studies on the structural and cultural sources of educational expansion and differentiation, and on the cultural and structural consequences of educational institutionalization. Research topics: education and nation building; education, mobility, and equality; education, international organizations, and world culture.","min_units":4,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"15:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}],[]],"secondary":[[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"17:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]},{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"17:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]},{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"09:00:00","end":"09:50:00"}]},{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"17:00:00","end":"18:15:00"}]}],[]]},
"306Y":{"department":"EDUC","number":"306Y","title":"Economic Support Seminar for Education and Economic Development","description":"Core economic concepts that address issues in education in developing and developed countries. Supply and demand, elasticity, discount rates, rate of return analysis, utility functions, and production functions. Corequisite: 306A. (Carnoy)","min_units":1,"max_units":1,"gers":[],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,false,true],"start":"14:15:00","end":"15:05:00"}]}],[],[]],"secondary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,false,true,false],"start":"16:15:00","end":"18:05:00"}]}],[],[]]},
"309X":{"department":"EDUC","number":"309X","title":"Educational Issues in Contemporary China (EDUC 109X)","description":"Reforms such as the decentralization of school finance, emergence of private schools, expansion of higher education, and reframing of educational policy to focus on issues of quality. Have these reforms exacerbated educational inequality.","min_units":3,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[true,false,false,false,false],"start":"14:15:00","end":"17:05:00"}]}]]},
"313X":{"department":"EDUC","number":"313X","title":"The Education of American Jews (JEWISHST 393X, RELIGST 313X)","description":"This course will take an interdisciplinary approach to the question of how American Jews negotiate the desire to retain a unique ethnic sensibility without excluding themselves from American culture more broadly. Students will examine the various ways in which people debate, deliberate, and determine what it means to be an \"American Jew\". This includes an investigation of how American Jewish relationships to formal and informal educational encounters through school, popular culture, religious ritual, and politics.","min_units":4,"max_units":4,"gers":[],"primary":[[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,false,true,false,false],"start":"09:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}],[],[]]},
"322":{"department":"EDUC","number":"322","title":"Discourse of Liberation and Equity in Communities and Classrooms (AFRICAAM 130)","description":"Issues and strategies for studying oral and written discourse as a means for understanding classrooms, students, and teachers, and teaching and learning in educational contexts. The forms and functions of oral and written language in the classroom, emphasizing teacher-student and peer interaction, and student-produced texts. Individual projects utilize discourse analytic techniques. Prerequisite: graduate status or consent of instructor.","min_units":3,"max_units":5,"gers":[],"primary":[[],[],[{"instructors":[],"meeting-times":[{"days":[false,true,false,false,false],"start":"09:00:00","end":"11:50:00"}]}]]},
